Question

A bowl is designed as the revolution of the region between 3 curves: \[z=5x-43\]

\[z=\frac{7}{100}x^2\]

\[z=0\]

The revolution occurs around the \(z\) axis. The bowl will be made of wood.


Notice the point of intersection is \((10, 7)\). Below is a wireframe animation of the bowl.


Find the volume of the wood composing the bowl. I’d recommend using the washer method. The tolerance is \(\pm 1\) cubic units.

Solution

We will use the washer method. Notice we can approximate the shape with a bunch of thin washers.


Each washer has two radii (inner and outer) and an infinitesimal thickness.


The infinitesimal volume for each washer can be expressed in terms of \(r\), \(R\), and \(dz\).

\[dV ~=~ \pi \left(R^2 - r^2\right) \, dz\]

We need to express \(R\) and \(r\) as functions of \(z\). Notice that \(R\) is equivalent to \(x\) in the linear equation and \(r\) is equivalent to \(x\) in the quadratic equation. Let’s start by finding \(R\) in terms of \(z\).

\[z = 5R-43\]

Solve for \(R\).

\[R = \frac{z+43}{5}\]

Now, let’s get \(r\) in terms of \(z\).

\[z = \frac{7}{100}r^2\]

Solve for \(r\).

\[r = \sqrt{\frac{100z}{7}}\]

To get the volume, we need to sum up a bunch of washer volumes as \(z\) progresses from 0 to 7.

\[V = \int_{z=0}^{z=7} dV\]

\[V = \int_{0}^{7} \pi\left(R^2-r^2\right)\,dz\]

\[V = \int_{0}^{7} \pi\left(\left(\frac{z+43}{5}\right)^2-\left(\sqrt{\frac{100z}{7}}\right)^2\right)\,dz\]

A constant multiplier can be pulled out of an integral.

\[V = \pi \int_{0}^{7} \left(\left(\frac{z+43}{5}\right)^2-\left(\sqrt{\frac{100z}{7}}\right)^2\right)\,dz\]

Honestly, at this point, you probably want to use Desmos. It understands definite integrals. You can get the integration symbol by typing int.

If you want to work it out algebraically, remember binomial expansion.

\[V = \pi \int_{0}^{7} \left(\frac{1}{25}z^2+\frac{86}{25}z+\frac{1849}{25}-\frac{100}{7}z\right)\,dz\]

Combine like terms.

\[V = \pi \int_{0}^{7} \left(\frac{1}{25}z^2+\left(\frac{86}{25}-\frac{100}{7}\right)z+\frac{1849}{25}\right)\,dz\]

Use the antiderivative. We use the square brackets and rewriting the limits to remember to put them into the antiderivative (and take a difference).

\[V = \pi \left[\frac{1}{75}z^3+\left(\frac{86}{50}-\frac{100}{14}\right)z^2+\frac{1849}{25}z\right]_{0}^{7}\]

Plug in the limits and take a difference.

\[V = \pi \left[ \left(\frac{1}{75}(7)^3+\left(\frac{86}{50}-\frac{100}{14}\right)(7)^2+\frac{1849}{25}(7)\right)-\left(\frac{1}{75}(0)^3+\left(\frac{86}{50}-\frac{100}{14}\right)(0)^2+\frac{1849}{25}(0)\right) \right]\]

Anything times 0 is 0.

\[V = \pi \left(\frac{1}{75}(7)^3+\left(\frac{86}{50}-\frac{100}{14}\right)(7)^2+\frac{1849}{25}(7)\right)\]

\[V=806.0488991\]
